    "view": {
      "representation": "view",
      "value": "<p>There is a dedicated PxrAovLight LOP. It is up to the user to create the Render Var / AOV used by the PxrAovLight. To do so, simply use a Render Var LOP and place it on the first input of the RenderMan Render Settings LOP (similar info at: <a href=\"/wiki/spaces/RFH27/pages/544641953/Setting+up+LPEs+in+Solaris\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544641953\" data-linked-resource-version=\"2\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">Setting up LPEs in Solaris</a> ). </p><p>It is possible to use light filters (<a href=\"/wiki/spaces/RFH27/pages/544641289/Light+Filters+in+Solaris\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544641289\" data-linked-resource-version=\"7\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">Light Filters in Solaris</a>) and light linking (<a href=\"/wiki/spaces/RFH27/pages/544641475/Light+Linking+in+Solaris\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544641475\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">Light Linking in Solaris</a>) on the PxrAovLight.</p><p>More information about PxrAovLight usage: <a href=\"/wiki/spaces/RFM27/pages/544541661/PxrAOVLight+in+Maya\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544541661\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">PxrAOVLight in Maya</a> </p>"
    }
  },
